Weird details about the pennies dissolving in nitric acid: You're right and wrong about the change from green to blue being a sign the copper is gone and it's now dissolving zinc. Zinc nitrate is actually colorless in solution and has nothing to do with the color change. The green and blue are both copper (II) nitrate solution, and the main difference is just time and the end of the copper reaction (regardless of whether or not there's also zinc present). At first, the solution is more concentrated, especially around the dissolution site (aka: the pennies), which results in copper and nitrate ions being close enough together to coordinate together (basically, they're still dissolved, but they're close enough together to interact with each other more than with water molecules). Almost as soon as the copper finishes dissolving, however, the copper nitrate spreads through the solution enough to coordinate all of the copper and nitrate ions with water molecules, resulting in a bright blue solution.

If you let the solution evaporate, you could end up with some copper nitrate crystals, which are also a very pretty blue.

What has worked for me in the past with headlight (I used to detail cars) I would use a very high grit sand paper (ex 1200 or 1500) and scuff the entire surface. Once it was sanded smooth, I would spray the entire surface with a clear coat and let it dry in a relatively warm, dust-free room. The clarity was about 95-98% brand new looking.

Yellowing of plastic headlights is due to the UV protectant on the surface of the lens. It reacts with the UV in sunlight and turns that yellow color. Your car tires do the same thing.
Once removed like this, you need to reapply a UV protectant. There are a number of off the shelf products that works well.
If you want it done the right way, you would need to wetsand and polish the lights, then apply a UV protectant and sealant.
